metadata.name: <iframes> #110
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: Tema #6
metadata.description:
Tema is the second in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art in the 1970s.

After gaining some traction with his original collection RAM, Zajec and his collaborating programmer Matjaz Hmeljak undertook a more complex algorithm titled "The Cube: Theme and Variation" (or TVC). The program laid out 8 unique elements in a grid, creating a three-dimensional viewing of objects in space. They published a paper about the underlying algorithm, found at: http://www.edwardzajec.com/tvc4/pil1/index.html

TVC was first printed in 1971, shortly after Zajec returned to Italy following his artistic studies in the US. It was programmed on an IBM 9044 & printed with a CalComp 563 plotter.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @christine_hall

metadata.name: Kyma #215
metadata.description:
Kyma (/kee-ma/, κύμα) is a Greek word meaning wave. It is my exploration of an acoustic phenomenon known as ‘Chladni Patterns’. 

Ernst Florens Friedrich Chladni was a German physicist and musician. He was a pioneer of modern acoustics and made numerous contributions to the field. Chladni's work had a significant influence on the development of modern music theory and the technology of musical instruments. In 1787, Chladni was trying to understand how sound waves propagate and interact with objects. By vibrating a metal plate and sprinkling sand on it, he observed that the sand arranged itself into distinct patterns. These patterns are created due to the interaction between the sound waves and the plate: the sound waves cause the plate to vibrate, which in turn causes the sand to move. The sand will move away from areas of high vibration and towards areas of low vibration. This creates a unique pattern of ridges, circles, and many other shapes.

Kyma continues this study by adding color, light, and composition to the equation. Each iteration is a unique combination of two Chladni plates with different characteristics, accompanied by a palette, background lighting, and variational drawing algorithm. Plates interact with each other, forming patterns from the small detailed net-like grid to megalithic sculptures of unknown creatures and windows to another worlds.

Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Rendering can be computationally heavy, please be patient and give it some time to draw.
Chrome is highly recommended for live mode and high res saving.

Made with love, math, and p5js. 

Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2400 x 1600
[2] - save PNG 4800 x 3200
[3] - save PNG 9600 x 6400
[4] - save PNG 14400 x 9600

metadata.name: Nanopanorama #49
metadata.description:
Distorted noise with weird textures and funky shapes rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm.

4671 characters of pure Javascript, no libraries.

Some options can be changed via the URL:

&lw=.25 : The linewidth in millimetres.
&d=.4 : Line density (multiplier to linewidth).
&h=235 : Page height in millimetres. The aspect ratio is 16:9, for a width of 420mm, suitable for A3 plotting.
&bg=1 : Set to 0 to remove background rectangle (recommended for plotting).

When plotting, it is recommended to use a path reordering / optimizing tool such as axicli or vpype to greatly reduce the plotting time.

metadata.name: Action; System #6
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Sand #95
metadata.description:
This project is a cellular automata that simulates falling sand. The falling is deterministic: each sand particle will fall to the same place each time the program is run. Some iterations eventually stop, some continue indefinitely.

The fun is that the project is implemented on a fragment shader. There is no array of grains of sand. Each pixel decides whether a grain of sand from a neighboring pixel will end up in it or not. This logic required a lot of banging my head against the wall, because the slightest mistake caused sand to disappear into nowhere or appear out of nothing and clutter up the entire space.

0…9 — set speed
space — pause
s — save picture
drag over — add more sand
shift+drag — erase

metadata.name: pixel cow #17
metadata.description:
The pixel cow is a Random Generated 64 PFP NFT.
This collection is manually designed.
The original Artwork was designed in 25 by 25 pixels and then resized to 1024 by 1024 resolution.
The number of Traits in this collection is 4 (47 layers) and it has the ability to make 9,702‬ different cow.

This project is available to collectors for free.

It's open for minting for up to a week, I'll burn the rest after a week

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #22
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden “template” canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‘template’ image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: Intertwined #213
metadata.description:
Intertwined began as a study of how to overlap randomized shapes at many intersection points while retaining consistency and physical accuracy. I initially envisioned vines growing on buildings, but over time Intertwined moved in a more abstract embroidery-like direction while retaining influences from that foundational concept.

Controls:
Key S: Save the output as a jpeg at the current resolution (only available once the piece has finished loading).
Key Arrow Up: Scale the resolution up by a multiple of 1080 pixels. There is no maximum. The current highest recommended scale-factor is 4x.
Key Arrow Down: Scale the resolution down by a multiple of 1080 pixels. 1080p is the minimum.
Key A: Skip the construction animation to show the final result immediately (please note that for pieces with a larger grid skipping the animation may cause a long pause).

Browser Support: Confirmed to work in Chrome Version 97.0.4692.71

metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #375
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, I’m always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. There’s something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition 

Commands in fullscreen mode:
S : Save current resolution
1 : Save 2000x3000px
2 : Save 4000x6000px
3 : Save 6000x9000px
4 : Save 8000x12000px
5 : Save 10000x15000px

(The higher the resolution, the longer it takes to render/save. use Chrome for best results.)
